How should a multi-format schema analysis tool reason about and report on the relationship between schemas defined in different formats that represent the same business entity — for example, an Order entity that is defined as an Avro schema for Kafka events, an OpenAPI response schema for the REST API, a GraphQL type for the GraphQL API, and a Protobuf message for the gRPC service?

This cross-format schema alignment problem is increasingly common in organizations that run polyglot API architectures. The same conceptual entity evolves independently in four different schema languages, with no tooling enforcing consistency between them. A field is renamed in the Protobuf definition but not in the OpenAPI spec. A new required field is added to the Avro schema but not reflected in the GraphQL type. These inconsistencies are invisible to single-format validators.

Think through what "equivalent" means across formats. The formats have different type systems: Avro has rich union types and named types, Protobuf has oneof and message nesting, JSON Schema / OpenAPI has allOf/oneOf/anyOf, and GraphQL has union types and interfaces. There is no universal mapping between these type systems. Some Avro constructs have no natural Protobuf equivalent and vice versa. Does this mean cross-format equivalence checking is fundamentally impossible, or are there sufficient structural correspondences to make partial equivalence checking useful?

Consider the simpler problem: field name and type consistency. If an Order entity has a field orderId: string in Avro and order_id: int64 in Protobuf, this is likely an inconsistency. A tool that can map snake_case to camelCase, apply common naming convention transformations, and flag type mismatches across formats would catch a real class of problems even without full semantic equivalence checking.

What metadata would a tool need to identify that two schemas in different formats represent the same entity? Options include: explicit annotation (a shared entity identifier in schema metadata), naming conventions (schemas named Order in all formats), or schema registry catalog entries that explicitly link format variants. Which of these approaches is most practical for organizations to adopt?

What would the output of cross-format schema consistency checking look like, and how should severity be assigned when formats diverge?
